%S A394710 8,9,12,16,18,20,21,24,28,33,35,40,44,50,52,54,56,60,65,68,69,72,76,
%T A394710 84,88,90,92,98,104,105,108,116,120,124,126,128,129,132,133,136,140,
%U A394710 145,148,150,152,156,161,164,165,168,172,180,184,188,192,195,198,200,204,212,216,220
%N A394710 Numbers k such that the sum of the number of divisors of its proper divisors including 1, each number of divisors to some power greater than zero, is equal to k itself.
%C A394710 12 seems to be the only number, for which the sum of d(divisors of n), number of divisors, is equal to the number itself.
%e A394710 Divisors of 12 are 1,2,3,4,6, d(1) = 1, d(2) = 2, d(3) = 2, d(4) = 3, d(6) = 4, and summed up, they give 1+2+2+3+4 = 12.
%e A394710 For 16, 16 has divisors 1,2,4,8, and d(1) = 1, d(2) = 2, d(4) = 3, and d(8) = 4, and 1+2+3^2+4 = 16.
%t A394710 q[k_] := Module[{d = DivisorSigma[0, Most[Divisors[k]]], e}, e = Join[{1}, Floor[Log[Rest[d], k]]]; AnyTrue[Tuples[Range /@ e], Total[d^#] == k &]]; Select[Range[2, 220], q] (* _Amiram Eldar_, May 04 2026 *)
%Y A394710 Cf. A192690, A000005, A394721, A192690.
